  "prompt": "What will be the derivative of x|x|, if x is -1",
  "response": "Let's solve this step by step:\n\n1) First, let's understand what x|x| means\n   \u2022 |x| represents the absolute value of x\n   \u2022 x|x| means x multiplied by the absolute value of x\n\n2) We'll use the definition of derivative: f'(x) = lim[h\u21920] (f(x+h) - f(x))/h\n\n3) When x = -1, let's consider the left-hand and right-hand derivatives separately\n\n4) By definition: \n   \u2022 When x < 0, |x| = -x\n   \u2022 When x > 0, |x| = x\n   \u2022 At x = 0, |x| = 0\n\n5) For x = -1:\n   x|x| = -1 * |-1| = -1 * 1 = -1\n\n6) For points near -1:\n   \u2022 If x is slightly less than -1, x|x| will be slightly less than 1\n   \u2022 If x is slightly more than -1, x|x| will be slightly more than 1\n\n7) The derivative at -1 is 1\n\nTherefore, the derivative of x|x| at x = -1 is 1.",
